5. Encoding - Categorical Data¶

4.2. Encoding - Categorical Data¶

4.2.1. Evaluation of best technique¶

The encoders we decide to use must be suitable for our dataset, and the most important factors to decide which method is the best includes:

  • count of unique values
  • ordinality nature of feature
  • whether features have a fixed and finite count of unique categories or not

Count of unique values

Features with unique values on val/test not seen on train dataset

In [22]:
mismatched_features = []

# Loop through each feature in X_train columns to check if its the same size as val/test
for feature in X_train.select_dtypes(include='object').columns:
    train_unique = set(X_train[feature].unique())
    test_unique = set(X_test[feature].unique())
    
    if train_unique != test_unique:
        # Find unique values in X_test that are not in X_train
        unique_in_test_not_train = test_unique - train_unique
        mismatched_features.append((feature, len(unique_in_test_not_train)))  # Store the count of unique values

# Print features where the unique values differ and how many unique values are not in train
if mismatched_features:
    print("Features with mismatched unique values between X_train and X_test:")
    for feature, unique_count in mismatched_features:
        print(f"- {feature}: {unique_count} unique values in X_test not in X_train")
else:
    print("No mismatched unique values between X_train and X_test.")
#improve code, to only include features with uniques that dont appear on train

Features with mismatched unique values between X_train and X_test:
- Carrier Name: 102 unique values in X_test not in X_train
- WCIO Part Of Body Code: 0 unique values in X_test not in X_train
- Zip Code: 2025 unique values in X_test not in X_train
- Body Part Group: 1 unique values in X_test not in X_train

4.2.2. Applying encoding techniques¶

Count Encoding Counts the number of ocurrences in each unique value and replace with count values- Useful for high number of unique values.

Considerations:

  • After this encoding, the features becomes numerical
  • By default, CountEncoder will assign a count of 0 to any category in X_test/X_val that was not present in X_train.

5. Target Class Balancing¶

We will apply hybrid resampling by undersampling majority classes and oversampling minority classes using SMOTE. This balances the dataset, improving the model’s ability to learn from all classes and enhancing performance on underrepresented ones.

In [36]:
target = 'Claim Injury Type'

# Apply undersampling for majority classes
undersampler = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy={
    2: 100000,  # Reduce class 2 to 100,000 samples
    4: 50000    # Reduce class 4 to 50,000 samples
}, random_state=42)

X_train_under, y_train_under = undersampler.fit_resample(X_train_num, y_train)

# Apply SMOTE for extreme minority classes
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy={
    1: 20000,
    7: 10000,
    8: 10000,
    6: 20000
}, random_state=42)

X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train_under, y_train_under)

print("Class distribution before resampling:", Counter(y_train))
print("Class distribution after resampling:", Counter(y_resampled))

# Confirm resampled data
X_resampled_df = pd.DataFrame(X_resampled, columns=X_train_num.columns)
y_resampled_df = pd.Series(y_resampled, name=target)

Class distribution before resampling: Counter({2: 203754, 4: 103955, 3: 48234, 5: 33796, 1: 8734, 6: 2948, 8: 329, 7: 68})
Class distribution after resampling: Counter({2: 100000, 4: 50000, 3: 48234, 5: 33796, 1: 20000, 6: 20000, 7: 10000, 8: 10000})

6. Data Scaling¶

We use a Normalization scaler, knowing the following assumptions:

  • it is sensitive to outliers - but we treated most of them
  • doesn't assume data is normally distributed - because in our case it isn't
In [41]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))

#fit to training data
X_train_num_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_resampled_df)
joblib.dump(scaler, 'scaler.pkl')

#transform the val amd test data
X_val_num_scaled = scaler.transform(X_val_num) # this will return an array
X_test_num_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test_num) # this will return an array

7.1.2. Correlation Indices¶

Step 1 Between input variables - Redundancy¶

Assessing the correlation between input variables is meaningful to identify pairs who are highly correlated. High correlation indicates redundancy, meaning that that both features provide similar information to the model- in such cases, one of the correlated features can be discarded. This helps to reduce multicollinearity and improve the model's interpretability and efficiency.
In this section, we are testing the input features for redundancy.

We start by examining our numeric features, to ensure that all of them are continuous or ordinal, in order to comply with assumptions of Kendall's Correlation.
Our target is treated as categorical, and for that reason we exclude Spearman's correlation as an applicable method.

In [48]:
def cor_heatmap(cor):
    cor_copy = cor.copy()
    
    mask_values = (cor_copy.abs() <= 0.7)
    
    mask_upper = np.triu(np.ones_like(cor_copy, dtype=bool))
    
    mask = mask_values | mask_upper
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
    sns.heatmap(cor, mask = mask, cmap = 'RdBu', vmax = 1, vmin=-1, center = 0,
            square = True, annot = True, linewidths = .5)

Correlation Heatmap: Kendall

In [50]:
def corr_pairs(corr, threshold):
    mask = np.tril(np.ones(corr.shape), k=-1).astype(bool)
    
    corr_lower = corr.where(mask)
    
    cor_pairs = corr_lower.unstack().dropna()
    cor_pairs = cor_pairs[(cor_pairs.abs() > threshold)]

    
    for pair, value in cor_pairs.items():
        feature_count_pair1 = len(corr[(corr[pair[0]].abs() > 0.2) & (corr[pair[0]].abs() < threshold)])
        feature_count_pair2 = len(corr[(corr[pair[1]].abs() > 0.2) & (corr[pair[1]].abs() < threshold)])
        
        print(f'{pair[0]} | significantly correlated with more {feature_count_pair1} features | or | {pair[1]} | significantly correlated with more {feature_count_pair2} features | {value:.2f}')

Step 2 Between output variable - Relevancy¶

Assessing the correlation between input feature and the output variable is meaningful to identify which features have stronger predictive power. Low correlation may indicate that a feature is less relevant, potentially being unimportant for our model- in such cases, the feature can be discarded.
Removing such features helps to improve the model's interpretability and efficiency, by reducing the noise. However, we want remove solely based on this correlation, since we could be overlooking nonlinear relationships.
In this section, we are testing the input features for relevancy against the target variable.

In [55]:
def plot_target_correlation(correlation_matrix, method_name, target_column='Claim Injury Type'):

    # Extract correlations for the target variable and remove self-correlation
    target_cor = correlation_matrix[target_column].drop(target_column)
    
    # Sort correlations in descending order
    target_cor_sorted = target_cor.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # Plot the correlation with the target variable
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    target_cor_sorted.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
    plt.title(f'{method_name} Correlation with {target_column}')
    plt.xlabel('Features')
    plt.ylabel('Correlation Coefficient')
    plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=0.5, linestyle='--')
    plt.show()

Correlation Bar Plot: Kendall

In [58]:
def corr_target(correlation_matrix, threshold, target_column='Claim Injury Type'):

    # Extract correlations for the target variable
    target_cor = correlation_matrix[target_column].drop(target_column)
    
    # Identify features with correlation below the threshold
    low_cor = target_cor[target_cor.abs() < threshold]
    
    return low_cor  # Return the low-correlation features as a Series

7.1.3. ANOVA¶

We use ANOVA, since it is applicable for both categorical and numerical input variables, and beacause the target variable's nature also complies with this method. This method doesn't assume data is normally distributed, making it a sound method for feature selection on this dataset.

With that being said, we begin by joinining both subsets of data, to assess this feature selection methods on the entire dataset:

7.3. Embedded Methods¶

7.3.1. Lasso¶

Lasso, or L1 Regularization, applies a regression model and is a suitable feature selection method for our dataset, as it helps in both regularization and feature selection.
Since our input variables are numerical, Lasso can perform effectively, allowing for automatic feature selection while improving model performance, by reducing overfitting.

    plt.show()

7.4. Standalone Methods¶

This supervised learning algorithm, just like Random Forest, selects features by measuring the level of impurity that each one reduced in the model.

model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train_num_scaled, y_resampled_df)

feature_importances = pd.Series(model.feature_importances_, index=X_train_num_scaled.columns)

mean_importance = feature_importances.mean()
selected_features_dt = feature_importances[feature_importances > mean_importance].index.to_list()

print(f"Selected features: {selected_features_dt}")

Selected features: ['Age at Injury', 'Attorney/Representative', 'Average Weekly Wage', 'Birth Year', 'Days from Accident to C-2', 'Days from Accident to Assembly', 'Log_Average_Weekly_Wage', 'Claim Antiguity', 'Forms Delivered Count', 'Carrier Name', 'County of Injury', 'Industry Code', 'WCIO Cause of Injury Code', 'WCIO Nature of Injury Code', 'WCIO Part Of Body Code', 'Zip Code', 'Body Part Group', 'Industry Group']

8. Final Insights¶

8.1. Final feature selection¶

The table below integrates the feature selection methods tested on each feature, keeping only features that were selected on majority of methods. It doesn't include features selected by RFE'S, which were excluded for optimization of model's performance:

In [85]:
data = {'Feature': X_train_num_scaled.columns}

data['Variance'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_variance else 'Not Tested' if feature not in X_train_num_scaled.columns else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['Kendall'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_kendall else 'Not Tested' if feature not in X_train_num_scaled.columns else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['Target Kendall'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_target_kendall else 'Not Tested' if feature not in X_train_num_scaled.columns else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['ANOVA'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_anova else 'Not Tested' if feature not in X_train_num_scaled.columns else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['LASSO'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_lasso else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
#data['RFE LR'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_rfe else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
#data['RFE SVM'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_svm else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['DT'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_dt else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]
data['RandomForest'] = ['Keep' if feature in selected_features_rf else 'Discard' for feature in X_train_num_scaled.columns]


fs_table = pd.DataFrame(data)
fs_table['Result'] = fs_table.iloc[:, 1:].apply(
    lambda x: 'Selected' if (list(x[x != 'Not Tested']).count('Keep') - 1) > list(x[x != 'Not Tested']).count('Discard') 
    else 'Not Selected', 
    axis=1)

feature_selection = fs_table[fs_table['Result'] == 'Selected']['Feature'].tolist()

def color_cells(val):
    if val == 'Keep':
        return 'background-color: lightgreen'
    elif val == 'Discard':
        return 'background-color: lightcoral'
    elif val == 'Selected':
        return 'background-color: lightgreen; border: 2px solid darkgreen; font-weight: bold'
    elif val == 'Not Selected':
        return 'background-color: lightcoral; border: 2px solid darkred; font-weight: bold'
    else:
        return ''

styled_fs_table = fs_table.style.applymap(color_cells, subset=fs_table.columns[1:])

styled_fs_table
